{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b12cee1d-7ea7-4c6e-a855-9fcad7e86c37","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't the standard MAUI API for this. You need **two things**:\n\n### 1. iOS — Disable safe area insets on the page\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n### 2. Android — Draw behind system bars\n\nIn your `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n    Window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    Window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n}\n```\n\n> **Note:** Android 15 (SDK 35) enforces edge-to-edge by default, but earlier versions need this opt-in.\n\n### 3. Make the Image fill the space\n\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n       VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n```\n\nThe padding you're seeing is the OS-reserved safe area / system bar insets — both platforms need to be told independently to let your content draw underneath them.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e38e2c9f-11ab-4055-abbb-6520340d3dac","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. The key issue is that in .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content:\n\n1. `IgnoreSafeArea` on the view itself (like the Image) is important\n2. On Android, you need to opt into edge-to-edge mode\n3. On iOS, `SafeAreaEdges` controls the safe area insets\n\n\n4. For .NET 10, I need to reconsider the exact API — `SafeAreaEdges` might not be the right property on ContentPage, and the approach differs between platforms. On iOS, `IgnoreSafeArea` on the view or parent layout is the way to go, while Android requires configuring the window to draw behind system bars. For iOS specifically, I can use the platform configuration API to disable the safe area with `SetUseSafeArea(false)`, either through code-behind or XAML with the appropriate namespace imports.\n\nOn Android, I need to configure the window to draw behind the system bars, and then make sure the Image itself stretches to fill all available space with proper aspect ratio settings.\n\nSetting up Android edge-to-edge rendering...","outputTokens":1394,"requestId":"7FC6:14B651:4440B6F:4ACACA4:69F159B5"},"id":"e82d3a38-1738-4cf7-b86b-d2714a49bd12","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:07:26.945Z","parentId":"538d4d73-a38e-4b54-856d-81e73e9d5d49"}
